erica. Beginning in 1951 when black high school students protested unequal facilities and continuing through the return of whites to public schools in the 1970s and 1980s, Bonastia describes the struggle over education during the civil rights era and the human suffering that came with it, as well as the inspiring determination of black residents to see justice served. Artfully exploring the lessons of the Prince Edward saga, Southern Stalemate unearths new insights about the evolution of modern conservatism and the politics of race in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCivil rights movementsxVirginiaxPrince Edward County. 0aCivil rights movementszVirginiazPrince Edward County. 0aEducational equalizationxVirginiaxPrince Edward County. 0aEducational equalizationzVirginiazPrince Edward County. 0aPublic schoolsxVirginiaxPrince Edward County. 0aPublic schoolszVirginiazPrince Edward County. 0aSchool integrationxVirginiaxPrince Edward County. 0aSchool integrationzVirginiazPrince Edward County. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  apublic education, learning, virginia, sociology, social studies, court order, desegregation, racism, race, united states of america, american history, 20th century, politics, political confrontation, integration, high school, equality, equal rights, equity, civil liberties, humanity, human suffering, justice, conservatism, prince edward county, resistance, white supremacy, federal government, justifications, activism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022606389840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226063911423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226063911/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 20